5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThough%20we%20humans%20remain%20yet%20a%20long%20way%20off%20in%20this%20chronicle%2C%20we%20might%20note%20this%20as%20the%20genesis%20of%20the%20fossil%20fuels%20we%20would%20eventually%20take%20as%20the%20lifeblood%20of%20our%20modern%20global%20civilisation%2C%20whose%20happenstance%20distribution%20around%20the%20world%20would%20become%20a%20primary%20driver%20of%20modern%20geopolitics%E2%80%94even%20impacting%20responses%20to%20the%20present%20war%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.planetcritical.com%2Fp%2Feverybody-wants-gazas-gas%3Futm_source%3Dsubstack%26utm_medium%3Demail%5C%22%3EGaza%3C%2Fa%3E.%20We%20might%20also%20observe%20that%20the%20Earth-system%20continuously%20reinvents%20itself%2C%20never%20returning%20to%20an%20identical%20previous%20state.%20Nor%20is%20there%20any%20final%20or%20fixed%20steady%20state%2C%20no%20destination%20or%20goal.%20There%20have%20been%20many%20different%20versions%20of%20this%20one%20Earth%2C%20and%20many%20more%20will%20come.%20There%E2%80%99s%20no%20reason%20to%20expect%20that%20the%20way%20we%E2%80%99ve%20known%20it%20since%20the%20time%20of%20written%20histories%20describes%20its%20%3Cem%3Enormal%3C%2Fem%3E%20or%20neutral%20state%2C%20the%20way%20it%E2%80%99s%20%3Cem%3Emeant%20to%20be%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20or%20the%20way%20we%20might%20be%20able%20to%20maintain%20it%20in%20support%20of%20our%20present%20way%20of%20life.%20Earth%20has%20known%20nothing%20but%20continuous%20change.%20And%20we%20humans%20are%20but%20one%20aspect%20of%20these%20ongoing%20changes%3A%20we%20too%20are%20recently%20grown%20forms%20of%20Earth%E2%80%99s%20living%20crust%2C%20who%20someday%20will%20be%20gone%20or%20changed%20unrecognisably%20by%20the%20forces%20of%20evolution.%20That%20is%20a%20law%20of%20life.%20It%20ebbs%20and%20flows.%20It%20transmutes%20itself.%20It%20is%20never%20static.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cnn.com%2F2022%2F09%2F06%2Fworld%2Fearliest-mammal-teeth-scn-scli-intl%2Findex.html%5C%22%3Efirst%20mammals%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%94small%2C%20shrew-like%20creatures%E2%80%94appeared%20around%20225%20million%20years%20ago.%20At%20the%20time%2C%20nearly%20all%20the%20world%E2%80%99s%20land%20was%20connected%20together%20into%20a%20single%2C%20giant%20landmass%2C%20a%20supercontinent%20we%20call%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3Dvb_TnPD9TRU%5C%22%3EPangaea%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Around%20180%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20Pangea%20began%20to%20break%20up%2C%20drifting%20into%20continents%20somewhat%20more%20familiar%20to%20us%20today.%20As%20the%20climate%20kept%20on%20fluctuating%2C%20new%20organisms%20continuously%20arose%2C%20some%20of%20whom%20were%20much%20better%20at%20digesting%20the%20woody%20trunks%20of%20trees%2C%20rotting%20them%20away%20and%20thus%20curtailing%20newer%20formations%20of%20coal.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEven%20while%20dinosaurs%20still%20tromped%20happily%20across%20insular%20India%2C%20volcanoes%20began%20to%20belch%20as%20the%20Indian%20plate%20crossed%20over%20%E2%80%98hot%20spots%E2%80%99%20in%20the%20Earth%E2%80%99s%20mantle.%20But%20following%20the%20impact%20of%20the%20Chicxulub%20meteor%20on%20the%20opposite%20side%20of%20the%20globe%2C%20those%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.smithsonianmag.com%2Fscience-nature%2Fmeteorite-killed-dinosaurs-also-triggered-underwater-volcanoes-180968106%2F%5C%22%3Evolcanoes%20boomed%20into%20overdrive%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20burying%20most%20of%20the%20island%20in%20lava%20and%20spewing%20massive%20quantities%20of%20gas%20into%20the%20atmosphere%20over%20the%20next%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.science.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1126%2Fscience.aac7549%5C%22%3Ehalf%20a%20million%3C%2Fa%3E%20This%20extreme%2C%20prolonged%20environmental%20disruption%20likely%20compounded%20and%20extended%20the%20extinction%20event%20triggered%20by%20the%20meteor%20strike.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMeanwhile%2C%20reptiles%20had%20grown%20gigantic.%20Dinosaurs%2C%20in%20their%20various%20forms%2C%20great%20and%20small%2C%20remained%20the%20dominant%20beasts%20on%20land%20for%20250%20million%20years.%20Their%20heyday%20only%20ended%2C%20one%20fine%20day%20about%2066%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20when%20the%20giant%20Chicxulub%20meteor%20crashed%20into%20the%20sea.%20The%20heat%20of%20the%20collision%20instantly%20incinerated%20large%20swathes%20of%20the%20planet%E2%80%99s%20surface.%20Fire%20and%20rocky%20debris%20rained%20down%20upon%20the%20land.%20The%20impact%20unleashed%20a%20mega-tsunami%20with%20waves%20hundreds%20of%20meters%20high.%20It%20forced%20a%20seismic%20response%20that%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fnews.berkeley.edu%2F2015%2F04%2F30%2Fdid-dinosaur-killing-asteroid-trigger-largest-lava-flows-on-earth%5C%22%3Ecaused%20swarms%20of%20volcanoes%3C%2Fa%3E%20around%20the%20globe%20to%20belch%20and%20spurt%20continuously%20for%20tens%20of%20thousands%20of%20years%2C%20burying%20millions%20of%20kilometres%20of%20land%20under%20burning%20lava%E2%80%94and%20shaping%20the%20geography%20of%20many%20lands%2C%20including%20the%20Deccan%20Plateau.%20This%20magnitude%20of%20devastation%20once%20again%20utterly%20revised%20life%20on%20Earth%2C%20in%20what%E2%80%99s%20referred%20to%20as%20the%20Fifth%20Great%20Mass%20Extinction%20Event%E2%80%94the%20fifth%20time%20that%20most%20species%20then%20existing%20on%20Earth%20rapidly%20died%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20as%20before%2C%20life%20eventually%20bounced%20back%20with%20even%20greater%20diversity.%20New%20mixes%20of%20forests%20grew.%20Birds%20now%20filled%20the%20skies.%20By%20forty%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20mammals%20were%20emerging%20as%20the%20most%20dominant%20class%20of%20creature%20on%20land%2C%20spreading%20themselves%20under%20steamy%20jungle%20canopies%20around%20the%20planet%2C%20some%20even%20sliding%20back%20into%20the%20oceans%2C%20evolving%20into%20whales%20and%20dolphins.%20This%20exuberant%20flowering%20of%20life%20was%20not%20quelled%20even%20as%20the%20planet%20embarked%20upon%20yet%20another%20cooling%20trend.%20Snow%20began%20to%20fall%20again%20after%20many%20millions%20of%20years%2C%20first%20in%20the%20mountains%20of%20Antarctica.%20Over%20the%20following%20millions%20of%20years%2C%20the%20world%E2%80%99s%20highest%20peaks%2C%20north%20and%20south%2C%20slowly%20donned%20mantles%20of%20ice.%20Earth%20had%20been%20encrusted%20in%20ice%20before%2C%20but%20not%20when%20it%20was%20also%20adorned%20by%20forests%20and%20grasslands%20swarming%20with%20legions%20of%20warm-blooded%20creatures%2C%20birds%20and%20mammals%2C%20amid%20the%20richest%2C%20densest%2C%20most%20diverse%20biota%20it%20had%20ever%20created.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20this%20cooling%2C%20drying%20climate%2C%20some%20forests%20in%20Africa%20were%20burning%20away%20into%20grasslands.%20It%20was%20then%20that%20our%20earliest%20hominid%20ancestors%E2%80%94two-legged%20apes%20of%20short%20stature%E2%80%94climbed%20down%20from%20their%20shrinking%20tree%20cover%20and%20strode%20onto%20the%20African%20savannas%2C%20some%20six%20million%20years%20ago.%20Like%20other%20primates%2C%20they%20probably%20used%20some%20tools%2C%20such%20as%20digging%20sticks.%20But%20over%20the%20next%20few%20million%20years%2C%20as%20their%20cognitive%20capacities%20were%20reshaped%20by%20their%20changing%20environment%2C%20they%20began%20noticing%20the%20properties%20of%20different%20types%20of%20stone%2C%20how%20best%20to%20break%20them%20into%20shapes%20useful%20for%20chopping%20things.%20They%20also%20came%20to%20understand%20some%20things%20about%20fire.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EExtreme%20vulcanism%20across%20insular%20India%20at%20the%20end%20of%20the%20Cretaceous%20Period%20contributed%20to%20the%20mass%20extinction%20event%20that%20ended%20the%20dinosaurs%E2%80%99%20reign.%20The%20resulting%20lava%20beds%20remain%20major%20geologic%20features%20across%20much%20of%20peninsular%20India.%20Today%20called%20the%20Deccan%20Traps%2C%20they%20still%20rank%20among%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpubs.geoscienceworld.org%2Fgsa%2Fgsabulletin%2Farticle-abstract%2F127%2F11-12%2F1507%2F126064%2FTriggering-of-the-largest-Deccan-eruptions-by-the%3FredirectedFrom%3Dfulltext%5C%22%3Emost%20extensive%20and%20voluminous%3C%2Fa%3E%20lava%20fields%20known%20on%20Earth.%20Some%20sixty-six%20million%20years%20later%2C%20people%20would%20carve%20Buddhist%20monasteries%20and%20Hindu%20temples%20into%20their%20cliff%20faces%20at%20Ajanta%20and%20Ellora.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBy%20two%20million%20years%20ago%2C%20when%20massive%20fields%20of%20ice%20had%20well%20taken%20hold%20of%20Antarctica%20and%20the%20far%20northern%20latitudes%2C%20our%20early%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Faustralian.museum%2Flearn%2Fscience%2Fhuman-evolution%2Fhominid-and-hominin-whats-the-difference%2F%5C%22%3Ehominin%3C%2Fa%3E%20ancestor%2C%20%3Cem%3EHomo%20erectus%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20had%20become%20recognisably%20human%2C%20though%20not%20quite%20identical%20to%20us%20(we%2C%20%3Cem%3EHomo%20sapiens%20sapiens%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20appeared%20a%20mere%20three%20hundred%20thousand%20years%20ago).%20With%20their%20well-developed%20stone%20tools%20and%20mastery%20of%20fire%2C%20%3Cem%3EH.%20erectus%3C%2Fem%3E%20ventured%20beyond%20Africa%2C%20eventually%20colonizing%20much%20of%20southern%20Eurasia%20from%20what%20today%20is%20Spain%20to%20India%20to%20China%20and%20the%20farthest%20reaches%20of%20peninsular%20southeast%20Asia%20(which%20would%20later%20become%20the%20islands%20of%20Indonesia).%20None%20of%20what%20followed%20would%20have%20been%20possible%20without%20both%20fire%20and%20a%20propensity%20to%20build%20thick%20social%20worlds%2C%20two%20aspects%20of%20being%20human%20that%20appear%20tightly%20linked%20and%20are%20the%20subject%